1
00:00:00,380 --> 00:00:02,080
The Big Short is probably one of the

2
00:00:02,080 --> 00:00:04,320
most popular films on the topic of investing.

3
00:00:04,860 --> 00:00:06,960
It's a star-studded movie that follows the

4
00:00:06,960 --> 00:00:09,060
real story of three groups of people who

5
00:00:09,060 --> 00:00:11,800
short, or bet against, the housing market for

6
00:00:11,800 --> 00:00:14,860
billions of dollars, right before the 2008 real

7
00:00:14,860 --> 00:00:15,520
estate crisis.

8
00:00:16,080 --> 00:00:17,760
As you might expect, our heroes end up

9
00:00:17,760 --> 00:00:18,740
making quite a bit of money.

10
00:00:19,320 --> 00:00:21,420
But how exactly does a short work?

11
00:00:21,900 --> 00:00:23,760
Well, in the movie, the positions are taken

12
00:00:23,760 --> 00:00:26,320
through what are known as swaps, a derivative

13
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:28,120
agreement that is taken with the banks.

14
00:00:28,120 --> 00:00:31,659
But for common investors, short positions typically involve

15
00:00:31,659 --> 00:00:34,540
individual stocks, making them easy enough to take.

16
00:00:35,080 --> 00:00:37,840
But be warned, shorting comes with a lot

17
00:00:37,840 --> 00:00:38,360
of risks.

18
00:00:38,820 --> 00:00:40,580
On top of charging you expenses you don't

19
00:00:40,580 --> 00:00:43,920
normally see with standard investing, shorting also offers

20
00:00:43,920 --> 00:00:46,200
a skewed payoff, where you face a limited

21
00:00:46,200 --> 00:00:49,680
upside and an uncapped downside, meaning you could

22
00:00:49,680 --> 00:00:52,860
lose an infinite amount of money, theoretically anyway.

23
00:00:53,260 --> 00:00:55,320
So before you decide to short something, let's

24
00:00:55,320 --> 00:00:57,600
go over the strategy and the risks involved

25
00:00:57,600 --> 00:00:58,840
on today's plain bagel.

26
00:01:02,050 --> 00:01:04,470
Shorting, also known as short selling, is a

27
00:01:04,470 --> 00:01:06,890
trading strategy where an investor sells a security

28
00:01:06,890 --> 00:01:08,790
today and buys it back in the future,

29
00:01:09,110 --> 00:01:10,770
hoping that the price of the security will

30
00:01:10,770 --> 00:01:11,290
go down.

31
00:01:11,670 --> 00:01:14,230
It's effectively the opposite approach to a traditional

32
00:01:14,230 --> 00:01:17,790
long position, where investors buy today and sell

33
00:01:17,790 --> 00:01:19,250
at some point in the future to cash

34
00:01:19,250 --> 00:01:21,450
in, hopefully after the price has gone up.

35
00:01:21,870 --> 00:01:24,190
It follows the same buy low sell high

36
00:01:24,190 --> 00:01:27,050
mentality as long investing, but it just reverses

37
00:01:27,050 --> 00:01:29,330
the order of the motto, so investors sell

38
00:01:29,330 --> 00:01:31,190
high today and hope that the price will

39
00:01:31,190 --> 00:01:32,930
go down so they can buy low in

40
00:01:32,930 --> 00:01:33,350
the future.

41
00:01:34,150 --> 00:01:36,370
Now, shorting a stock is a bit more

42
00:01:36,370 --> 00:01:38,410
complicated than going long on a position.

43
00:01:38,770 --> 00:01:41,390
So let's go through a running example to

44
00:01:41,390 --> 00:01:43,930
explain how the strategy works and the risks

45
00:01:43,930 --> 00:01:44,510
it poses.

46
00:01:45,110 --> 00:01:47,130
Imagine you have two investors who decide to

47
00:01:47,130 --> 00:01:49,350
take opposite positions in plain bagel co.

48
00:01:49,490 --> 00:01:51,850
The company's stock currently has a market price

49
00:01:51,850 --> 00:01:52,250
of $10.

50
00:01:52,990 --> 00:01:55,010
Investor A decides to buy 1,000 of

51
00:01:55,010 --> 00:01:56,930
these stocks, thereby investing $10,000.

52
00:01:57,430 --> 00:01:59,710
While investor B decides to short 1,000

53
00:01:59,710 --> 00:02:02,610
stocks, thereby selling $10,000 worth of the

54
00:02:02,610 --> 00:02:03,030
investment.

55
00:02:03,690 --> 00:02:04,930
Now, I know what you're thinking.

56
00:02:05,370 --> 00:02:06,770
How the hell do you sell a stock

57
00:02:06,770 --> 00:02:08,169
that you don't own?

58
00:02:08,889 --> 00:02:11,330
Well, oftentimes the process involves selling a borrowed

59
00:02:11,330 --> 00:02:11,790
security.

60
00:02:12,370 --> 00:02:14,370
For example, in a brokerage account, you can

61
00:02:14,370 --> 00:02:16,690
often sell a position by borrowing a stock

62
00:02:16,690 --> 00:02:18,970
from your broker and then shorting that way,

63
00:02:19,370 --> 00:02:21,290
leaving you with the proceeds from the sale.

64
00:02:21,290 --> 00:02:23,430
The money you make from the sale obviously

65
00:02:23,430 --> 00:02:25,850
doesn't really belong to you, since you sold

66
00:02:25,850 --> 00:02:27,170
someone else's stock to get it.

67
00:02:27,610 --> 00:02:29,570
But eventually, when you buy the security back,

68
00:02:29,770 --> 00:02:31,790
known as covering your short, you'll be able

69
00:02:31,790 --> 00:02:33,690
to return the stock and keep whatever money

70
00:02:33,690 --> 00:02:35,970
is left over, which is how you profit

71
00:02:35,970 --> 00:02:36,590
from the trade.

72
00:02:37,090 --> 00:02:38,770
So going back to our example, if the

73
00:02:38,770 --> 00:02:41,750
stock price falls from $10 to $5, investor

74
00:02:41,750 --> 00:02:44,050
A will lose $5,000 while investor B

75
00:02:44,050 --> 00:02:46,350
will gain $5,000, since they'll be able

76
00:02:46,350 --> 00:02:48,010
to buy the stock back for a lower

77
00:02:48,010 --> 00:02:50,270
price and keep the remaining sales proceeds.

78
00:02:50,270 --> 00:02:52,270
On the other side of things, if the

79
00:02:52,270 --> 00:02:55,270
stock price increases from $10 to $15, investor

80
00:02:55,270 --> 00:02:57,790
A will be up $5,000 while investor

81
00:02:57,790 --> 00:02:59,130
B will be down $5,000.

82
00:02:59,470 --> 00:03:01,330
But this raises an interesting question.

83
00:03:01,750 --> 00:03:03,830
Up until this point, investor B hasn't actually

84
00:03:03,830 --> 00:03:05,350
contributed any of their own money.

85
00:03:05,790 --> 00:03:07,210
So how is he going to buy back

86
00:03:07,210 --> 00:03:09,270
the stock for more money than what's in

87
00:03:09,270 --> 00:03:09,730
the account?

88
00:03:10,470 --> 00:03:12,290
Well, this is where the concept of margins

89
00:03:12,290 --> 00:03:13,010
come into play.

90
00:03:13,610 --> 00:03:15,710
You see, to short a position, an investor

91
00:03:15,710 --> 00:03:17,790
needs to post what's known as an initial

92
00:03:17,790 --> 00:03:20,690
margin of 50% into their account to

93
00:03:20,690 --> 00:03:22,750
act as a buffer should the investment lose

94
00:03:22,750 --> 00:03:23,210
value.

95
00:03:23,730 --> 00:03:25,990
This means that investor B would have contributed

96
00:03:25,990 --> 00:03:28,330
$5,000 of his own funds at the

97
00:03:28,330 --> 00:03:30,670
beginning of our example to accommodate for any

98
00:03:30,670 --> 00:03:31,070
losses.

99
00:03:31,350 --> 00:03:33,910
The amount still belongs to the investor, but

100
00:03:33,910 --> 00:03:36,110
it's held as collateral by the broker to

101
00:03:36,110 --> 00:03:37,870
ensure that investor B can afford to buy

102
00:03:37,870 --> 00:03:38,770
back the share in the future.

103
00:03:39,470 --> 00:03:41,470
Investor B will also be responsible for what

104
00:03:41,470 --> 00:03:43,770
are known as margin calls, a process that

105
00:03:43,770 --> 00:03:45,810
occurs when the margin becomes insufficient.

106
00:03:45,810 --> 00:03:48,070
For example, in the event that the share

107
00:03:48,070 --> 00:03:51,090
price rises to $15, investor B would receive

108
00:03:51,090 --> 00:03:53,530
a margin call to replenish their cash buffer

109
00:03:53,530 --> 00:03:56,170
based on what's known as the maintenance margin,

110
00:03:56,530 --> 00:03:58,190
since there's no more wiggle room in the

111
00:03:58,190 --> 00:04:00,190
account to accommodate for further losses.

112
00:04:00,730 --> 00:04:02,890
So a big difference between shorting and going

113
00:04:02,890 --> 00:04:04,650
long a position is that you can only

114
00:04:04,650 --> 00:04:05,870
short in a margin account.

115
00:04:06,390 --> 00:04:08,550
While this has its downsides, it does add

116
00:04:08,550 --> 00:04:10,210
leverage to the investor's return.

117
00:04:10,750 --> 00:04:11,670
What do I mean by that?

118
00:04:12,110 --> 00:04:13,310
Well, let's go back to our example.

119
00:04:13,310 --> 00:04:15,470
Let's say that our share price falls from

120
00:04:15,470 --> 00:04:16,149
$10 to $5.

121
00:04:16,690 --> 00:04:18,829
This would lead investor A to lose $5

122
00:04:18,829 --> 00:04:21,130
,000 and investor B to gain $5,000.

123
00:04:21,690 --> 00:04:24,310
On an absolute basis, these returns equate one

124
00:04:24,310 --> 00:04:26,910
another, but on a percentage basis, taking into

125
00:04:26,910 --> 00:04:29,150
account margins, they're actually quite different.

126
00:04:29,710 --> 00:04:31,710
You see, investor A has lost roughly 50

127
00:04:31,710 --> 00:04:34,330
% of their investment, but since investor B

128
00:04:34,330 --> 00:04:37,170
has only contributed $5,000 of his own

129
00:04:37,170 --> 00:04:39,830
money to this margin account, he's actually gained

130
00:04:39,830 --> 00:04:42,530
100% of his investment, double the percentage

131
00:04:42,530 --> 00:04:43,410
of investor A.

132
00:04:43,870 --> 00:04:46,770
Because borrowing is involved with shorting, investor B

133
00:04:46,770 --> 00:04:49,750
will see his returns amplified, though this goes

134
00:04:49,750 --> 00:04:50,650
both ways.

135
00:04:51,190 --> 00:04:53,830
Percentage losses in the short position will be

136
00:04:53,830 --> 00:04:55,530
double what they might have been for investor

137
00:04:55,530 --> 00:04:55,890
A.

138
00:04:56,410 --> 00:04:58,070
So a decline of 50% for investor

139
00:04:58,070 --> 00:05:00,870
A would translate into a 100% decline

140
00:05:00,870 --> 00:05:01,770
for investor B.

141
00:05:02,590 --> 00:05:04,710
So short positions not only flip the percentage

142
00:05:04,710 --> 00:05:07,550
return received by investors, but they also amplify

143
00:05:07,550 --> 00:05:09,810
them, both on the way up and the

144
00:05:09,810 --> 00:05:10,250
way down.

145
00:05:10,250 --> 00:05:12,870
But here's where we get into the distinct

146
00:05:12,870 --> 00:05:14,550
disadvantages of a short position.

147
00:05:15,230 --> 00:05:18,470
Namely, short positions come with unique costs that

148
00:05:18,470 --> 00:05:20,410
a standard long investor won't face.

149
00:05:20,990 --> 00:05:22,990
For example, if the stock you borrowed pays

150
00:05:22,990 --> 00:05:25,170
a dividend, you'll actually need to pay this

151
00:05:25,170 --> 00:05:27,310
amount to your broker, meaning that you'll face

152
00:05:27,310 --> 00:05:29,510
a cost equal to whatever dividend the stock

153
00:05:29,510 --> 00:05:29,910
pays.

154
00:05:30,570 --> 00:05:33,250
Short positions also charge investors an interest rate

155
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:35,090
on the value of the stock you borrowed.

156
00:05:35,470 --> 00:05:37,790
After all, since you are borrowing and selling

157
00:05:37,790 --> 00:05:40,450
someone else's security, you need to compensate them

158
00:05:40,450 --> 00:05:41,990
in the same way that you would compensate

159
00:05:41,990 --> 00:05:44,050
a bank with interest on a loan.

160
00:05:44,770 --> 00:05:46,630
Typically, the rate charged on a short position

161
00:05:46,630 --> 00:05:49,190
can range anywhere from 2.5 to 20%,

162
00:05:49,190 --> 00:05:51,050
but it can be higher for what are

163
00:05:51,050 --> 00:05:53,490
known as hard-to-borrow stocks, highly volatile

164
00:05:53,490 --> 00:05:55,010
or small-cap positions.

165
00:05:55,750 --> 00:05:58,170
So, needless to say, shorting a stock can

166
00:05:58,170 --> 00:06:00,090
be quite a bit more expensive than a

167
00:06:00,090 --> 00:06:00,590
simple buy.

168
00:06:00,970 --> 00:06:02,790
But for the most part, these expenses are

169
00:06:02,790 --> 00:06:03,110
fair.

170
00:06:03,570 --> 00:06:05,570
The interest makes sense since you are taking

171
00:06:05,570 --> 00:06:08,370
a leveraged position, and since you are trying

172
00:06:08,370 --> 00:06:10,810
to inverse the return of a long position,

173
00:06:11,150 --> 00:06:12,610
it's only natural that you pay out the

174
00:06:12,610 --> 00:06:14,070
dividend received from the stock.

175
00:06:14,710 --> 00:06:17,270
But there are some absolute disadvantages involved with

176
00:06:17,270 --> 00:06:19,790
a short strategy, some of which may very

177
00:06:19,790 --> 00:06:21,430
well turn you off the idea of ever

178
00:06:21,430 --> 00:06:22,310
trying to short a stock.

179
00:06:22,810 --> 00:06:25,430
For one, short strategies face what's known as

180
00:06:25,430 --> 00:06:27,650
buy-in risk, the chance that a broker

181
00:06:27,650 --> 00:06:30,110
will make you prematurely cover your position.

182
00:06:30,650 --> 00:06:32,710
This can occur for a number of reasons.

183
00:06:32,930 --> 00:06:34,670
A broker may need to return a stock

184
00:06:34,670 --> 00:06:36,690
to the portfolio they took it from, or

185
00:06:36,690 --> 00:06:38,470
the stock may simply see a surge in

186
00:06:38,470 --> 00:06:38,770
demand.

187
00:06:39,350 --> 00:06:41,150
But the end result is that you may

188
00:06:41,150 --> 00:06:43,190
be forced to close your position at any

189
00:06:43,190 --> 00:06:43,590
time.

190
00:06:44,170 --> 00:06:47,010
This is a pretty significant drawback, especially when

191
00:06:47,010 --> 00:06:49,090
it comes to waiting out market volatility.

192
00:06:49,830 --> 00:06:52,030
In our example, perhaps investor B is confident

193
00:06:52,030 --> 00:06:55,090
that certain factors, whether it be regulation or

194
00:06:55,090 --> 00:06:57,710
technological change, will cause the stock to crash

195
00:06:57,710 --> 00:06:58,670
in two years' time.

196
00:06:59,150 --> 00:07:00,730
But if the price surges in the near

197
00:07:00,730 --> 00:07:03,030
term, they may be forced to realize a

198
00:07:03,030 --> 00:07:04,850
loss even if they end up being right.

199
00:07:05,390 --> 00:07:07,190
On top of this, when shorting a position,

200
00:07:07,470 --> 00:07:09,230
you may experience what's known as a short

201
00:07:09,230 --> 00:07:12,390
squeeze, when a heavily shorted stock sees its

202
00:07:12,390 --> 00:07:15,390
price surge because the investors shorting the stock

203
00:07:15,390 --> 00:07:16,650
need to cover their position.

204
00:07:17,250 --> 00:07:19,650
Since investors who short sell have an appropriately

205
00:07:19,650 --> 00:07:22,830
shorter time horizon than long investors, there's a

206
00:07:22,830 --> 00:07:24,990
chance that they buy back the stock around

207
00:07:24,990 --> 00:07:27,010
the same time, which can lead to a

208
00:07:27,010 --> 00:07:28,770
surge in the price and make it harder

209
00:07:28,770 --> 00:07:30,850
for you to cover your own position without

210
00:07:30,850 --> 00:07:31,770
realizing a loss.

211
00:07:32,470 --> 00:07:34,370
So, as you can see, there are some

212
00:07:34,370 --> 00:07:38,130
distinct disadvantages with shorting a position, which alone

213
00:07:38,130 --> 00:07:39,370
may lead you to stay away.

214
00:07:39,950 --> 00:07:42,490
But perhaps the biggest risk with short positions

215
00:07:42,490 --> 00:07:44,250
has to do with their skewed payoff.

216
00:07:44,890 --> 00:07:46,710
With our two investors longing in shorting the

217
00:07:46,710 --> 00:07:49,990
$10 stock, we face two risk-reward profiles.

218
00:07:50,510 --> 00:07:52,350
On the one hand, investor A can theoretically

219
00:07:52,350 --> 00:07:54,250
earn an infinitely high return.

220
00:07:54,810 --> 00:07:57,030
The $10,000 investment in the $10 stock

221
00:07:57,030 --> 00:08:00,050
could double, triple, quadruple in value as the

222
00:08:00,050 --> 00:08:03,290
stock price climbs to $20, $30, $40 or

223
00:08:03,290 --> 00:08:03,550
higher.

224
00:08:04,010 --> 00:08:06,090
On the downside, the most she can lose

225
00:08:06,090 --> 00:08:08,410
is the money she's invested, the $10,000,

226
00:08:08,870 --> 00:08:10,850
which would only happen if the stock fell

227
00:08:10,850 --> 00:08:12,810
to zero, a pretty drastic outcome.

228
00:08:13,550 --> 00:08:15,990
Now, investor B actually flips the risk-reward

229
00:08:15,990 --> 00:08:16,270
here.

230
00:08:16,650 --> 00:08:18,370
If the stock drops down to zero, ignoring

231
00:08:18,370 --> 00:08:20,490
fees, they can achieve a 200% return

232
00:08:20,490 --> 00:08:22,170
since they are able to keep the $10

233
00:08:22,170 --> 00:08:24,870
,000 profits from their $5,000 investment.

234
00:08:25,430 --> 00:08:27,270
On the other hand, if the stock instead

235
00:08:27,270 --> 00:08:31,309
climbs to $20, $30, $40 or higher, they

236
00:08:31,309 --> 00:08:35,110
can lose 200%, 400%, 600% or more.

237
00:08:35,630 --> 00:08:37,630
This means that you can lose a lot

238
00:08:37,630 --> 00:08:39,890
more money than what you've initially invested.

239
00:08:40,370 --> 00:08:42,750
And indeed, this very feature has had devastating

240
00:08:42,750 --> 00:08:43,850
impacts on investors.

241
00:08:44,590 --> 00:08:46,830
This is why many investors tend to stick

242
00:08:46,830 --> 00:08:47,970
with long-only positions.

243
00:08:48,270 --> 00:08:50,230
For many, the return is simply not worth

244
00:08:50,230 --> 00:08:50,690
the risk.

245
00:08:50,950 --> 00:08:52,150
And on top of the fact that you're

246
00:08:52,150 --> 00:08:54,370
going against the natural upward bias of stocks,

247
00:08:54,750 --> 00:08:56,470
you're more or less betting against a company

248
00:08:56,470 --> 00:08:58,530
that is actively trying to prove you wrong.

249
00:08:59,310 --> 00:09:01,150
Short selling certainly does play an important role

250
00:09:01,150 --> 00:09:02,150
in the world of investments.

251
00:09:02,510 --> 00:09:03,710
And indeed, you can make a lot of

252
00:09:03,710 --> 00:09:05,850
money by placing a short bet against a

253
00:09:05,850 --> 00:09:06,930
deteriorating stock.

254
00:09:07,230 --> 00:09:08,610
But if you're looking to speculate with short

255
00:09:08,610 --> 00:09:09,850
selling, tread lightly.

256
00:09:10,450 --> 00:09:11,590
You may end up buying off a lot

257
00:09:11,590 --> 00:09:12,310
more than you can chew.

258
00:09:12,890 --> 00:09:13,590
Thanks for watching.

259
00:09:13,810 --> 00:09:14,850
If you like this video, make sure to

260
